CONTEXT:/n/n For men and women, “business casual” dress tends to include a reinterpretation of at least one
formal power cue into a more casual ensemble (Rucker, Anderson, and Kangas 1999). A jacket (often a blazer or
sports jacket) may be worn with more casual khaki pants and a tie. Sweaters are permissible with a skirt or
pants. Shoes are often more casual and comfortable. A great amount of variety is present, but in-cludes more
limits than does “casual dress.” Some offices allow highly casual dress, including jeans and shorts.
Permissible styles vary greatly across firms, geographic areas, and occupations (Ogle and Damhorst 1999) and
age and gender of workers (Tootelian 2003).
History of the Trend

Youth Studies, 1993.
Willis, Paul. Profane Culture. London: Routledge and Kegan
Paul, 1978.
Wilson, Elizabeth. Adorned in Dreams: Fashion and Modernity.
London: Virago, 1985.
David Muggleton

BIBLIOGRAPHY
Benaim, Laurence. Pants, Trousers: A Walking History. Paris: Vilo
Publishing, 2001,
Martin, Richard, and Harold Koda, eds. Jocks and Nerds: Men’s
Style in the Twentieth Century. New York: Rizzoli, 1989.
Polhemus, Ted. Street Style From Sidewalk to Catwalk. London:
Thames and Hudson, Inc., 1994.
Wolter, Gundula. Die Verpackung des männlichen Geschlechts. Eine
illustrierte Kulturgeschichte der Hose. Marburg: Jonas Verlag, 1991.
A history of men’s trousers.
Gundula Wolter

Conclusion
It may well seem that the dress-for-success formulas of the 1980s have long since been replaced by more
“individuality” and “creativity” in clothing. Indeed, the back-lash to all these rules came in the 1990s with
“dress downon Friday” introduced in offices both in the United States and United Kingdom. While we may like to
think we are“individual” and while dress choice is welcomed by some, the business and professional worlds
remain conservative/n

CONTEXT:/n/n For men and women, “business casual” dress tends to include a reinterpretation of at least one
formal power cue into a more casual ensemble (Rucker, Anderson, and Kangas 1999). A jacket (often a blazer or
sports jacket) may be worn with more casual khaki pants and a tie. Sweaters are permissible with a skirt or
pants. Shoes are often more casual and comfortable. A great amount of variety is present, but in-cludes more
limits than does “casual dress.” Some offices allow highly casual dress, including jeans and shorts.
Permissible styles vary greatly across firms, geographic areas, and occupations (Ogle and Damhorst 1999) and
age and gender of workers (Tootelian 2003).
History of the Trend

Willis, Paul. Profane Culture. London: Routledge and Kegan
Paul, 1978.
Wilson, Elizabeth. Adorned in Dreams: Fashion and Modernity.

Style in the Twentieth Century. New York: Rizzoli, 1989.
Polhemus, Ted. Street Style From Sidewalk to Catwalk. London:
Thames and Hudson, Inc., 1994.
Wolter, Gundula. Die Verpackung des männlichen Geschlechts. Eine
illustrierte Kulturgeschichte der Hose. Marburg: Jonas Verlag, 1991.

Conclusion
It may well seem that the dress-for-success formulas of the 1980s have long since been replaced by more
“individuality” and “creativity” in clothing. Indeed, the back-lash to all these rules came in the 1990s with
“dress downon Friday” introduced in offices both in the United States and United Kingdom. While we may like to
think we are“individual” and while dress choice is welcomed by some, the business and professional worlds
remain conservative/n

CONTEXT:/n/n For men and women, “business casual” dress tends to include a reinterpretation of at least one
formal power cue into a more casual ensemble (Rucker, Anderson, and Kangas 1999). A jacket (often a blazer or
sports jacket) may be worn with more casual khaki pants and a tie. Sweaters are permissible with a skirt or
pants. Shoes are often more casual and comfortable. A great amount of variety is present, but in-cludes more
limits than does “casual dress.” Some offices allow highly casual dress, including jeans and shorts.
Permissible styles vary greatly across firms, geographic areas, and occupations (Ogle and Damhorst 1999) and
age and gender of workers (Tootelian 2003).
History of the Trend

Youth Studies, 1993.
Willis, Paul. Profane Culture. London: Routledge and Kegan
Paul, 1978.
Wilson, Elizabeth. Adorned in Dreams: Fashion and Modernity.
London: Virago, 1985.
David Muggleton

BIBLIOGRAPHY
Benaim, Laurence. Pants, Trousers: A Walking History. Paris: Vilo
Publishing, 2001,
Martin, Richard, and Harold Koda, eds. Jocks and Nerds: Men’s
Style in the Twentieth Century. New York: Rizzoli, 1989.
Polhemus, Ted. Street Style From Sidewalk to Catwalk. London:
Thames and Hudson, Inc., 1994.
Wolter, Gundula. Die Verpackung des männlichen Geschlechts. Eine
illustrierte Kulturgeschichte der Hose. Marburg: Jonas Verlag, 1991.
A history of men’s trousers.
Gundula Wolter

Conclusion
It may well seem that the dress-for-success formulas of the 1980s have long since been replaced by more
“individuality” and “creativity” in clothing. Indeed, the back-lash to all these rules came in the 1990s with
“dress downon Friday” introduced in offices both in the United States and United Kingdom. While we may like to
think we are“individual” and while dress choice is welcomed by some, the business and professional worlds
remain conservative/n

A black-tie event is a sea of ebony and ivory—all
men, although from different ranks in society, at least vi-sually and superficially are united by convention.
Formalwear not only functions as a social leveling device for men at a gathering, but it also provides a
uniform back-drop (or perhaps, “black-drop”) for the female guests who are not restricted to the color black
for their gowns. Formal clothes have an air of assured authority and confidence about them and are generally
resistant to fashion, although of course some designers attempt to play with their strictures from collection
to collection. But customers always seem to revert to the history, tradition, and timeless style of the
unshakable classics.
As the Victorian middle class grew and male attire became increasingly homogenous (dark, somber coat and
jacket in a limited range of cuts), ties became a signpost of social status (Gibbings 1990). Evolution of the
club, school, and regimental ties meant that those in the know were able to identify a man’s social ranking
based primarily on the color and pattern of the tie they wore. Even in the twenty-first century, some sectors
of society still believe that the stripes on one’s tie define an individual to himself and to others (Sells
1998). The expression “old school tie” reflects membership of a specific, privileged class.
Although women had worn cravats and scarves in various forms alongside their male contemporaries primarily out
of coquetry (Chaille 1994), it was in the late nineteenth and early twentieth century that neckwear took a
more prominent role in men’s fashion. Both male and female apparel was constructed of functional, utilitarian
fabrics such as calico and flannel. The simple color palette for both sexes consisted of gray, brown, cream,
and pale green tones. Women commonly wore loose-fitting, long-sleeved dresses, aprons, and bonnets. Men wore
unstructured coats, plain hats, trousers, and buckled shoes. For both sexes, functional garment details were
also restricted, the use of buttons was restricted, and small accessor- ies or jewelry was forbidden. The
commonality of dress between the sexes not only created group uniformity but also visually reinforced their
detachment from the wider society.
Quaker dress maintained popularity within marginal society, but the most popular dress for men was the black-
tie event. New York: Perennial, 2001.
Alistair O’Neill
FORMAL WEAR, MEN’S The quintessence of uni-
form elegance in men’s wear must surely be those
nearly changing garments described as “formal.” The exact opposite of “casual” clothes, men’s formal garments
are as utilitarian and ennobling as they are leveling. This might seem a contradiction in terms, but one has
only to think of a “black-tie” event to realize that at least en masse, the uniform nature of the
clothes—coded and easily recognizableglobally—places all men in the same category, much like a uniform does
for the army, navy, or air force. But unlike the military, which has panoplies of different ranks, a tangible
difference in provenance can be evinced in formal wear. Is that suit custom-made? Is that rented? Is that a
hand-me-down? Is this a lucky find in a vintage market?
A black-tie event is a sea of ebony and ivory—all
men’s dress must exhibit signs that the wearer is a man of leisure.
